<http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/mspecies/sex001>
    bibo:endPage "17" ;
    bibo:issue "942" ;
    bibo:journal "Mammalian Species" ;
    bibo:pubDate "2017-05-01" ;
    bibo:startPage "1" ;
    bibo:volume "49" ;
    dc:creator "Rose, Robert K.; Pemberton, David A.; Mooney, Nick J.; Jones, Menna E." ;
    dc:date "2017" ;
    dc:title "Sarcophilus harrisii (Dasyuromorphia: Dasyuridae)" ;
    fabio:hasPart <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573412>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573416>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573414>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573418>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573422>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573420> ;
    a fabio:JournalArticle .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573412>
    dc:description "Fig. 1.—An alert young Sarcophilus harrisii showing black coat with white marking on chest, prominent vibrissae, wet nose, and nearly naked ears. About 13% are all black. The sexes are similar except that males" ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/4573412/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573416>
    dc:description "Fig. 2.—Dorsal, ventral, and lateral views of skull and lateral view of mandible of Sarcophilus harrisii (adult male, United States National Museum, USNM 252733) collected 4 June 1928; locality unknown.The specimen exhibits the tiny cranium, typical of marsupials. Photograph by Sam Hughes used with permission." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/4573416/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573414>
    dc:description "Fig. 3.—The distribution of Sarcophilus harrisii has been restricted to the island state of Tasmania, Australia, in historic times. The land area of the larger island of Tasmania, 64,519 km2, is approximately equivalent to that of the states of West Virginia or South Carolina, United States. Note the temperate location, 41–42°S." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/4573414/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573418>
    dc:description "Fig. 4.—Typical aggression between adult Sarcophilus harrisii, whether at a carcass or in contention for mates. Note the massive head, the postures during threat displays, the differential placement of white markings, and the pale cheeks of the older animal on the right, the result of scars from past conflicts. Photograph by Christo Baars used with permission." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/4573418/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573422>
    dc:description "Fig. 5.—The 1st symptoms of the fatal disease, Devil Facial Tumor Disease, often are patches of redness on the palate, lips, and snout. Note the relatively unscarred cheeks of this young adult Sarcophilus harrisii. Photograph by Christo Baars used with permission." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/4573422/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4573420>
    dc:description "Fig. 6.—Adult Sarcophilus harrisii (photographed prior to 1996) with what is now called Devil Facial Tumor Disease. Such gross deformities of the advanced stages of the disease prevent normal feeding behavior, leading to death by starvation or secondary infections. At the time this photograph was taken by Christo Baars, Devil Facial Tumor Disease was undocumented in the literature." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/4573420/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

